## 3. Prioritization Rubric

Rank candidates by expected value, not by ease alone. For each, weigh:

- Information gain: how much the result would change the next decision. A {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} that resolves an open risk in `docs/project/project-status.md` ranks high; a marginal tweak ranks low.
- Cost: compute, wall-time, and effort. Use `docs/operations/time-estimation.md` for any wall-time figure rather than guessing.
- Blocking power: whether other work or a writeup claim waits on it. A baseline that unblocks every later comparison ranks above an isolated improvement.
- Risk reduction: whether it tests an assumption that, if wrong, would invalidate later work.

Prefer the cheapest {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} that resolves the biggest open uncertainty. Keep one lever per {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} so the verdict is attributable. When two candidates tie, pick the one that unblocks the most downstream work.
